          "subscriptions_url" => "https://api.github.com/users/seejee/subscriptions",
          "type" => "User", "url" => "https://api.github.com/users/seejee"}},
      %{"body" => "OK things:\r\n\r\n1) the weird rebase thing between the first and second commits.\r\n\r\n2) logging - there's a lot of it, and we're using `warn`, `debug`, and `log` variously.  I don't necessarily mind the logging but i'm also not sure where it comes out or at what level, and some of it seems pretty informative (whereas some of the rest seems like debugging code).  If it's all useful and intelligible, then by all means, but I had a difficult time figuring out whether it was supposed to be there or not.  Example:\r\n\r\n```\r\neasyrtc.connect(config.appName, function(id){\r\n  console.log(`Now connected to ${id} as ${appData.user.username}`);\r\n}, function(errorCode, errorText){\r\n  console.log(\"Connection error \", errorCode, \" text: \", errorText);\r\n});\r\n```\r\nThese logs look good!  Not sure if they should be `log` or `debug` or whatevs, but they're definitely informative.\r\n\r\n```\r\nconsole.log(\"boostrapped\");\r\n```\r\nThis one looked like it might just be debugging that got left in.  If it's useful and current, can we make the messages more informative, like 'Audio client was bootstrapped successfully with webrtc'\r\n\r\n3) I understand the desire to not back up PR's, but I wonder if this could have been done more granularly.  It may not even be the number of things tackled here as much as adding the client all in one big commit (and not understanding the client very well) that made it feel complex.  (nothingtodohere), just posing the comment.\r\n",
